The provided Lean code defines locally modelled spaces, manifolds, and orbifolds. The final goal is to prove that the quotient space used to model orbifolds (quotient of `Eucl n` by a finite subgroup of linear equivalences) is locally compact.

`Eucl n` is a finite-dimensional real vector space (isomorphic to $\mathbb{R}^n$), so it is a locally compact space. The group $\Gamma$ acts on `Eucl n` by linear equivalences, which are homeomorphisms. The projection map onto the orbit space $\pi : \text{Eucl } n \to (\text{Eucl } n)/\Gamma$ is an open map because $\Gamma$ acts by homeomorphisms. Since the projection is a surjective open continuous map and the domain is locally compact, the codomain is locally compact.

We use the lemma `IsOpenMap.locallyCompactSpace` which states that the image of a locally compact space under a surjective open continuous map is locally compact. We establish the openness of the quotient map using `MulAction.isOpenMap_quotient_mk`, which requires a `ContinuousConstSMul` instance (satisfied since $\Gamma$ acts by linear equivalences, which are continuous).

```lean
/-- The quotient spaces that orbifolds are modelled on are locally compact. -/
instance {n : ℕ} {Γ : {Γ : Subgroup ((Eucl n) ≃ₗ[ℝ] (Eucl n)) | Finite Γ}} :
    LocallyCompactSpace (MulAction.orbitRel.Quotient Γ (Eucl n)) := by
  letI : Setoid (Eucl n) := MulAction.orbitRel Γ (Eucl n)
  have : ContinuousConstSMul Γ (Eucl n) := ⟨fun g ↦ g.1.continuous⟩
  have h : IsOpenMap (Quotient.mk : Eucl n → MulAction.orbitRel.Quotient Γ (Eucl n)) :=
    MulAction.isOpenMap_quotient_mk
  exact h.locallyCompactSpace continuous_quotient_mk surjective_quotient_mk
```
